<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-02-26T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-02-26T06:00:00-05:00" n="97" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d97">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 793.94/242.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-26T19:00:00+08:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 26, 1915—7 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>My telegram of February 23, 8 p.m. At Sino-Japanese diplomatic conference
                            yesterday the opening of additional treaty ports in Shantung was agreed
                            to. The Chinese Government refused to accept the <pb facs="0214" n="98" xml:id="pg_98"/> wording of preamble of Article II that “the Chinese
                            Government has always acknowledged the special position enjoyed by Japan
                            in South Manchuria and Inner Mongolia” and they will continue to resist
                            the attempt to have a special status of Japan in that region formally
                            sanctioned. Next meeting Sunday [the 28th].</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>